==Trivia==
*In the comics, John Walker was a former [[United States Army]] soldier who was originally known as the '''Super-Patriot''', an anti-hero who was the dark reflection of [[Steve Rogers|Captain America]] and his views on patriotism. Walker later took over the mantle of Captain America after Steve Rogers abandoned the role. After Rogers reassumed the role of Captain America, Walker became a government operative and occasional vigilante/mercenary codenamed '''U.S. Agent'''.
*Walker is 6'1.<ref>[[:File:John Walker Trading Card Back.jpg|John Walker Trading Card]]</ref>

==Behind the Scenes==
*[[Wyatt Russell]] originally read for the part of [[Steve Rogers]] for ''[[Captain America: The First Avenger]]'', although he was ultimately not chosen for the part.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qMY-QhGNYzU Wyatt Russell's Transition to the Film Business]</ref>
*[[Justin Eaton]] and [[Lloyd Pitts]] were stunt doubles for [[Wyatt Russell]] in the role of U.S. Agent.<ref>[https://www.instagram.com/p/COjldhKA5wR/?igshid=1ng5iy20d6pz3 Russell & Eaton]</ref><ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm4281147/ Lloyd Pitts]</ref>
*[[Chris Heeder]] was an acting double for [[Wyatt Russell]] in the role of U.S. Agent.
*In early drafts of ''[[Thunderbolts*]]'', U.S. Agent was going to be the final villain the team fought in the end. [[Eric Pearson]] wanted to put emphasis on [[Valentina Allegra de Fontaine|Valentina]]'s manipulation by convincing him that the serum was wearing off. When Pearson realized that he wanted the heroes to persevere with them hugging at the end, he decided that it would be better suited for a villain that they couldn't punch, hence why [[Sentry]] was added.<ref>[https://screenrant.com/thunderbolts-villain-john-walker-sentry-void-writer-explained/ Thunderbolts* Writer Reveals John Walker Was Originally The Main Villain And Why It Became Sentry/The Void Instead]</ref>

